name: gud iivning
shortDescription: "Gud iivning" is a greeting used in Jamaican Patois to say "Good evening".
longDescription: "Gud iivning" is a common phrase used in Jamaican Patois to greet someone in the evening hours. It is similar to saying "Good evening" in English and is a polite way to acknowledge someone during this time of day.
sampleSentence: "Gud iivning, Maas Joe" (Good Evening, Mr Joe)

name: elo
shortDescription: "Elo" is a standard greeting used in Jamaican Patois

name: gud maanin
shortDescription: "Gud maanin" is a greeting used in Jamaican Patois to say "Good morning".
longDescription: "Gud maanin" is a phrase in Jamaican Patois that is used to greet someone in the morning hours. It is a polite way to acknowledge someone during this time of day.

name: wah gwaan
shortDescription: "Waah Gwaan" is a casual greeting used in Jamaican Patois to say "What's going on?" or "What's up?"
longDescription: A casual expression for saying “What’s going on” or “what’s up”. Different variations of “Wah gwaan” may be used but they all have the same meaning. These include: “Wah Deh Gwaan” or “Whatta Gwaan”.

name: gud nait
shortDescription: "Gud nait" is a greeting used in Jamaican Patois to say "Good night".
longDescription: "Gud nait" is a phrase in Jamaican Patois that is used to say "Good night" to someone. It is a common way to end a conversation or to say goodbye at night.
sampleSentence: "Mi a guh sleep now, gud nait." (I am going to sleep now, good night.)

name: sari
shortDescription: "Sari" is a phrase used in Jamaican Patois to express sympathy or apology.
longDescription: Sari is a phrase in Jamaican Patois that is used to express sympathy or apology. It is similar to saying "I'm sorry" in English.
sampleSentence: "Mi cyaan come to di party tonite, sari bout dat." (I can't come to the party tonight, sorry about that.)

name: patty
longDescription: Popular Jamaican pastry that contains various fillings and spices such as beef, chicken or cheese that is baked in a golden yellow tinted flaky shell. In Jamaica, the patty is often paired with coco bread when being eaten.
sampleSentence: Mi woulda luv fi nyam a beef patty right now

name: breakfas
shortDescription: "Breakfas" is a mealtime in Jamaican Patois that refers to breakfast.
longDescription: "Breakfas" is a term used in Jamaican Patois to refer to the morning meal or breakfast. It is typically eaten early in the morning, and usually consists of a light meal of bread, tea, porridge, or some other similar food.
sampleSentence: "Mi mada cook some ackee and saltfish fi breakfas dis mawnin." (My mother cooked some ackee and saltfish for breakfast this morning.)

name: lonch
shortDescription: Lonch is a mealtime in Jamaican Patois that refers to lunch.
longDescription: "Lonch" is a term used in Jamaican Patois to refer to the midday meal or lunch. It is typically eaten around midday, and usually consists of a more substantial meal than breakfast, such as rice and peas, fried chicken, or other similar dishes.
sampleSentence: "Mi a goh grab a likkle jerk chicken fi mi lonch today." (I am going to get some jerk chicken for my lunch today.)

name: dinna
shortDescription: Dinna is a mealtime in Jamaican Patois for dinner/supper.
longDescription: "Dinna" is a term used in Jamaican Patois to refer to the evening meal or dinner. It is typically eaten in the late afternoon or early evening and usually consists of a heavier meal than lunch or breakfast, such as rice and peas, stewed chicken, or other similar dishes.
sampleSentence: "Mi a goh mek some brown stew fish fi mi dinna tonight." (I am going to make some brown stew fish for my dinner tonight.)

name: kafi
shortDescription: "Kafi" is the Jamaican Patois term for coffee.
longDescription: "Kafi" refers to the popular hot beverage made from roasted coffee beans. Jamaican coffee is known for its rich flavor and is produced in various regions of the country.

name: hegg
shortDescription: Hegg is a common food item in Jamaican cuisine that refers to an egg.
longDescription: "Hegg"  is a common food item in Jamaican cuisine and is used in a variety of dishes, breakfast meals, or as a side dish to complement other dishes.
sampleSentence: Mi mada boil up some hegg fi me

name: bota
shortDescription: "Bota" is a common food item in Jamaican cuisine that refers to butter.
longDescription: "Bota" is the Jamaican Patois term for butter, a dairy product made from milk or cream. It is used in a variety of Jamaican dishes, such as fried dumplings, and as a spread on bread or crackers.
sampleSentence: "Yu bread bota pan two side". (You are very fortunate)

name: shap
shortDescription: "Shap" is a common word used in Jamaican Patois that refers to a shop.
longDescription: "Shap" in Jamaican Patois refers to a small retail store or shop that sells goods such as groceries, snacks, toiletries, and other household items. It is a popular place for locals to purchase everyday items or run errands.
sampleSentence: "Mi a guh run guh a shap fi buy some bread and cheese." (I am going to run to the shop to buy some bread and cheese.)

name: kash
shortDescription: "Kash" is a slang term in Jamaican Patois that refers to money.
longDescription: Kash" in Jamaican Patois is a slang term that refers to money, specifically cash. It is often used in everyday conversations or in music and other forms of entertainment.
sampleSentence: "Mi haffi go hustle fi some kash fi pay mi bills." (I have to go hustle for some cash to pay my bills.)

name: tingz
shortDescription: "Tingz" is a slang term in Jamaican Patois that refers to things or stuff.
longDescription: "Tingz" in Jamaican Patois is a slang term that refers to things or stuff. It is commonly used in everyday conversations and can refer to any object or item.
sampleSentence: "Mi haffi go buy some tingz fi mi new apartment." (I have to go buy some things for my new apartment.)

name: risiit
shortDescription: "Risiit" is a term in Jamaican Patois that refers to a receipt.
longDescription: "Risiit" in Jamaican Patois refers to a receipt, which is a document that serves as proof of purchase or transaction. It is commonly used in everyday transactions, such as in stores or restaurants.
sampleSentence: "Mi need a risiit fi di tings mi buy inna di supermarket." (I need a receipt for the things I bought at the supermarket.)

name: venda
shortDescription: "Venda" is a term in Jamaican Patois that refers to a vendor.
longDescription: "Venda" in Jamaican Patois refers to a vendor, which is a person who sells goods or services. It can refer to a street vendor, a market vendor, or a vendor in a store or other retail location.
sampleSentence: "Mi a guh buy some fruit from di venda inna di market." (I am going to buy some fruit from the vendor in the market.)

name: klouz
shortDescription: "Klouz" is a term in Jamaican Patois that refers to clothes or clothing.
longDescription: "Klouz" in Jamaican Patois refers to clothes or clothing. It is a common term used in everyday conversations and can refer to any type of garment or article of clothing.
sampleSentence: "Mi need fi wash mi klouz fi di week." (I need to wash my clothes for the week.)
